4. Using amtune after setup is run
----------------------------------
After setup is run, amtune directory will be created under
<TOOLS_DIR>/<FAM_INSTANCE_NAME>/bin, which would contain amtune or amtune.bat
script for tuning operating systems (Solaris 9, 10 or later or RedHat Enterprise
AS 4 or 5), web containers (Sun Application Server 9.1/Glassfish v2 or Sun Web Server
7.0 U3), Sun Directory Server 5.1/5.2 or 6.3 as SM (Service Management) and UM (User
Manangement) data stores, as well as Federated Access Manager configuration
values stored in SM and UM data stores.

To run amtune, amtune-env.properties must be customized to specify installation/
instance locations, passwords, review or change mode and other required parameters for
the components mentioned above.

5. Executing amtune on a remote Sun Directory Server machine.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Step 1. FTP or copy over famAdminTools.zip to the remote Sun DS machine.
Step 2. Unzip famAdminTools.zip.
Step 3. Create <TOOLS_DIR>/<FAM_URI_DIR>/unix/bin/amtune on Unix/Linux
        and TOOLS_DIR>\<FAM_URI_DIR>\windows\bin\amtune on Windows   
Step 4. Copy <TOOLS_DIR>/template/unix/bin/amtune/amtune.template on Unix/Linux to
        <TOOLS_DIR>/<FAM_URI_DIR>/unix\bin/amtune/amtune and
        <TOOLS_DIR>\template\windows\bin\amtune\amtune.bat.template on Windows to
        <TOOLS_DIR>\<FAM_URI_DIR>\windows\bin\amtune\amtune.bat
Step 5. Set values for TOOLS_HOME and JAVA_HOME in
        <TOOLS_DIR>/<FAM_URI_DIR>/unix/bin/amtune/amtune on Unix/Linux and
        <TOOLS_DIR>\<FAM_URI_DIR>\windows\bin\amtune\amtune.bat on Windows.   
Step 6.  Edit amtune-env.properties file with DS information.
Step 7.  Execute amtune on Unix/Linux and amtune.bat on Windows.